# Plain-Language Guides

**Read before editing:** `docs/lesson-01/plain-language.md`, `docs/lesson-04/plain-language.md`.

## Purpose

Simplest accurate version of the full lesson. Someone confused by the full guide should understand the core ideas here.

## Required structure

```markdown
# Lesson N: Topic — Plain-Language Guide

Intro paragraph linking to [full lesson](lesson-NN-....md), quick study, quiz.

---

## Summary
2–4 sentences. Bold key terms.

---

## The one-sentence version
Single sentence a student could recite.

---

## [Topic sections with plain headers]
Tables, analogies, ASCII or mermaid diagrams...

---

## The whole lesson on one napkin   ← optional but preferred for Lesson 1-style
Compact ASCII summary block

---

## Where to go next
Links back to full guide, quick study, quiz.
```

## Writing rules

- **Analogies first** — airline trip for layers, building/hallways for IGP vs BGP (`lesson-04/plain-language.md`)
- **Tables over prose** for comparisons and timelines
- **Jargon immediately translated** — "BGP (Border Gateway Protocol)" on first mention, then "BGP"
- **Memory tricks** as short bold lines — `**Memory trick:** IGP = hallways...`
- **Key takeaways** bullet lists after dense sections

## Relationship to full guide

- Cover the same concepts; omit proof-level detail and long algorithm walkthroughs
- Link to full guide for "when you want exam detail"
- If full guide has a diagram essential to understanding, reuse the same `images/...` reference

## What NOT to do

- Do not use exam-prep admonition blocks meant for full guides — use a simple intro paragraph
- Do not paste full lesson sections verbatim
- Do not add `<quiz>` blocks
- Do not introduce concepts from later lessons without a one-line "we'll cover this in Lesson N" note
- Do not use condescending tone — plain-language means clear and accessible, not childish
